   "source": [
    "# 🛒 NumPy Retail Sales Analysis Challenge\n",
    "\n",
    "Welcome to the **Retail Store Sales Analysis Challenge**! In this beginner-friendly challenge, you'll use **NumPy** to analyze a small retail dataset. Imagine you're a data analyst at a store, and the manager has asked for quick insights into recent sales.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll be working with weekly sales data for a few departments over a month. Your job is to convert this data into a NumPy array and perform some basic analysis. Don't worry, we'll guide you through each step. Let's dive in! 😃"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c1b15c1d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data Overview 📊\n",
    "Below is the sales data for three departments over four weeks (in dollars):\n",
    "\n",
    "| Department   | Week 1 | Week 2 | Week 3 | Week 4 |\n",
    "|-------------|-------:|-------:|-------:|-------:|\n",
    "| Electronics | 2500   | 2700   | 2600   | 2800   |\n",
    "| Clothing    | 5000   | 5200   | 5100   | 5300   |\n",
    "| Grocery     | 9200   | 9100   | 9300   | 9400   |\n",
    "\n",
    "*Departments in order:* Electronics (index 0), Clothing (index 1), Grocery (index 2). Each column is a week (Week 1–Week 4)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c4e81f1f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Run this cell to set up the sales data (nested list format)\n",
    "sales_data = [\n",
    "    [2500, 2700, 2600, 2800],  # Electronics dept sales for Week 1-4\n",
    "    [5000, 5200, 5100, 5300],  # Clothing dept sales for Week 1-4\n",
    "    [9200, 9100, 9300, 9400]   # Grocery dept sales for Week 1-4\n",
    "]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87f7cb2c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Challenge Tasks 📝\n",
    "We'll accomplish the following using NumPy:\n",
    "- **Create** a NumPy array from the nested sales list.\n",
    "- **Index** the array to find all weekly sales for a specific department.\n",
    "- **Slice** the array to find all department sales for a specific week.\n",
    "- **Sum** the data to get total sales for each department.\n",
    "- **Mean** (average) the data to get average sales per week across departments.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Each step below contains instructions and an example of the **expected output** for verification.*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "63beb17e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 1: Create the NumPy Array 🔢\n",
    "First, let's convert the sales data (currently a Python list of lists) into a NumPy array. \n",
    "1. **Import NumPy** (if you haven't already) and create a NumPy array called `sales_array` from `sales_data`.\n",
    "2. Display `sales_array` to confirm its contents and structure.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "76c63163",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "sales_array = np.array(sales_data)\n",
    "sales_array"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a6e2e4c0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "array([[2500, 2700, 2600, 2800],\n",
    "       [5000, 5200, 5100, 5300],\n",
    "       [9200, 9100, 9300, 9400]])\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "32d3251f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 2: Retrieve Department Sales 🔍\n",
    "Now, let's extract data for a specific department. \n",
    "- Use **indexing** to get the sales numbers for the second department (Clothing) across all weeks.\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Remember:* NumPy uses 0-based indexing. Clothing is index 1 in our `sales_array`.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "3e21675e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# All weeks for department at index 1 (Clothing)\n",
    "dept2_sales = sales_array[1]\n",
    "dept2_sales"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3e96cfa8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "array([5000, 5200, 5100, 5300])\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "076bebda",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 3: Retrieve Week Sales 📅\n",
    "Next, the manager wants to see the sales for **all departments in the last week**. \n",
    "- Use **slicing** to get the sales figures for Week 4 (the last column of the array) for every department.\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Hint: Use `:` to select all rows, and index `-1` for the last column.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "0b948c1a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Sales for all departments in week 4 (last week)\n",
    "week4_sales = sales_array[:, -1]\n",
    "week4_sales"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3d27c996",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "array([2800, 5300, 9400])\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8eb47ff9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 4: Total Sales per Department 💰\n",
    "Now let's find **total sales for each department** over the 4 weeks. \n",
    "- Use NumPy's **sum** function to calculate the sum of sales for each department (hint: sum over the columns for each row).\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Hint: You can use `sales_array.sum(axis=1)` to sum across columns of each row.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "48a5d228",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Total sales for each department (over all weeks)\n",
    "total_per_dept = sales_array.sum(axis=1)\n",
    "total_per_dept"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7f0bec6a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "array([10600, 20600, 37000])\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0e47c0cb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 5: Average Weekly Sales 🧮\n",
    "Finally, let's find out the **average sales per week** across all departments. \n",
    "- Use NumPy's **mean** function to calculate the mean of each week's sales (hint: average over the rows for each column).\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Hint: You can use `sales_array.mean(axis=0)` to get the mean of each column.)*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "848f967e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Average sales for each week across all departments\n",
    "avg_per_week = sales_array.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "avg_per_week"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d4c786ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Expected output:**\n",
    "```\n",
    "array([5566.66666667, 5666.66666667, 5666.66666667, 5833.33333333])\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
